Software Development Models describe the process followed to develop software step-by-step from requirement gathering to delivery and maintenance.

Each model defines:
  How work is organized
  When testing happens
  How changes are handled

1. Waterfall Model
Definition
Waterfall model is a linear and sequential SDLC model where each phase must be completed before moving to the next phase.

Phases :
       Requirement Analysis
         System Design 
     Development (Coding)
         Testing
        Deployment
       Maintenance
Explanation :
Requirements are collected first.
Design is prepared based on requirements.
Developers write code.
After development, testing begins.
Product is deployed to users.

Advantages
 Simple and easy to understand
 Clear documentation
 Well structured

Disadvantages
 Changes are difficult later
 Testing starts very late
 Not suitable for changing requirements

Best Used For
Small projects
Stable requirements

2. V-Model (Verification & Validation Model)
Definition
V-Model is an extension of the Waterfall model where testing activities are planned parallel to development phases.

Structure
Verification Phase        Validation Phase

Requirement             Acceptance Testing
System Design           System Testing
Architecture Design     Integration Testing
Coding                  Unit Testing
Explanation

Each development stage has a corresponding testing stage.

Example:
Requirement → Acceptance Test planning
Design → System test planning

Advantages
 Early defect detection
 Better quality assurance
 Clear testing strategy

Disadvantages
Less flexible
Not suitable for frequent requirement changes

Used In
Banking systems
Healthcare software

3. Agile Model
Definition
Agile is an iterative and incremental model where software is developed in small cycles called Sprints.
Process
Plan → Design → Develop → Test → Review → Release
(repeated every sprint)
Each sprint usually lasts 2–4 weeks.

Key Features
Continuous testing
Customer involvement
Frequent releases
Quick feedback

Advantages
   Flexible to changes
   Faster delivery
   Better customer satisfaction

Disadvantages
   Requires experienced team
   Documentation may be less

Popular Agile Frameworks
Scrum
Kanban

4. Spiral Model
Definition
Spiral model combines Waterfall + Iterative model and focuses mainly on risk analysis.

Steps in Each Spiral
Planning
Risk Analysis
Development
Testing
These steps repeat in loops (spirals).

Advantages
 Risk identification early
 Suitable for large projects

Disadvantages
 Expensive
 Complex management

Used For
Large enterprise systems
High-risk projects

5. Incremental Model
Definition
Software is developed and delivered in small functional parts (increments).
Example
  Version 1 → Login feature
  Version 2 → Dashboard
  Version 3 → Payment module

Advantages
  Early product delivery
  Easy testing
  Changes manageable

Disadvantages
   Requires proper planning
